</p>
<p>
      “My Prosecco Bot!” screamed the automaton, crouching over the cobblestones, scooping the glass up and holding up to his chest in despair. The workers loading the decommissioned wine bots onto the hunting party’s cart were holding their ears, squinting in both physical pain and in anticipation of a brass backhand from an enraged Merlot Bot.
</p>
<p>
      Merlot Bot had retrofitted his previously decommissioned and lobotomized wine bots to act as acorn feeders in the line that would lead the Butterfly Boar towards a prepared killing ground. With something as large and recklessly powerful as the Butterfly Boar, he had been prepared for some casualties, but had hoped for a nobler end for Prosecco Bot, who had always been quick with a joke during their time on the Bacchus.
</p>
<p>
      Merlot Bot played a MIDI file of a deep breath, and turned calmly towards the workers. “It’s OK boys,” said Merlot Bot. “Part of the job. Please continue.”
</p>
<p>
      What should his LED say? Forgive? Forget? It was blank, and black. He stared at the wagon filled with his brothers and sisters. Their once sparkly white or lusciously red vintages had been replaced with dun acorns, their limbs shorn off, their LEDs pried out, and their brass heads hammered into spigots. They would hang, upside down, on wooden tripods, and kick out acorns when
      triggered by the seismic trampling of an approaching Butterfly Boar. For now they sat stock still, almost shoulder to shoulder, save for the packing straw. Prosecco Bot has been the last. Maybe he had been pushing the workers too hard. He helped them replace Prosecco Bot’s empty space with more straw, sent them off with a bottle of yesterday’s vintage, and swept up the remains himself.
